data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()`. It asserts the type **and** returns the cast value in one step, replacing the brittle manual cast (which throws `InvalidCastException` instead of a clear test failure):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

If the type is wrong, you get a proper assertion failure message instead of an unhandled exception. The generic overload (MSTest v3+) returns the typed object so you can continue asserting on it.
